  "texts": [
    "Instead of a holistic goal of generating the correct response to the task input, attributable generation usually targets on two critical aspects: citation quality and the information correctness of the model response.",
    "The citation quality can be further assessed by two dimensions.",
    "The first dimension checks if a generated sentence is related to and can be supported by the corresponding cited reference(s).",
    "Another dimension inspects if any cited reference in the generation is redundant.To address these challenges, we resort to two training algorithms, namely rejection sampling (RS) and reinforcement learning (RL), and propose to use fine-grained rewards as training signals to teach an LM (e.g., LLaMA 2 (Touvron et al., 2023)) to generate attributable responses.",
    "We leverage the fine-grained automatic evaluation functions from Gao et al. (2023b) to provide localized (sentencelevel) and specialized (citation quality or response correctness) reward signals as fine-grained rewards.For training, we adapt from the fine-grained RL algorithm in Wu et al."
